Project Everest (Microsoft Research, INRIA, CMU, MIT) verifies the cryptographic stack from primitives up to TLS:

- **HACL\*** — verified primitives (Curve25519, Poly1305, ChaCha20, etc.), shipped in Mozilla NSS, Linux kernel via WireGuard, mbedTLS, Microsoft WinQuic, Tezos blockchain, ElectionGuard SDK;
- **EverCrypt** — verified cryptographic provider with provider-agnostic API and runtime multiplexing between HACL\* (C) and ValeCrypt (assembly);
- **EverParse** — verified parser combinators for binary protocols;
- **miTLS** — verified TLS implementation.

The shipping evidence: HACL\* primitives are in production at Mozilla (Firefox NSS — Curve25519, ChaCha20, Poly1305 since NSS 3.33+), in the Linux kernel's Wireguard implementation, in mbedTLS, in Microsoft Azure cryptographic stacks (WinQuic), in the Tezos blockchain, and in the ElectionGuard SDK. Status (as of 2026-04): consumer/integration list reflects publicly documented deployments; exact module coverage and version pin per downstream are time-sensitive.

**The deepest real-world deployment of formal verification for memory-safe code.** The lesson: cryptographic primitives are the killer app for formal verification — small, performance-critical, well-specified, and security-load-bearing.
